Overall, Thor: Love and Thunder to be comic book-y in spirit, but to its own detriment, as it is all over the place tonally and completely devoid of the groundedness and focus that Ragnarok had to leave itself open for involvement. 2/5

Granted, that is a testament to the character work in the script considering Thor and Jane had built mental walls to keep an outward appearance of strength, but if the main characters don't feel in danger or are ignoring their personal stakes, there's no reason for investment.

The majority of the action looks cheaper than other blockbusters this time around, and this entry in the MCU is obnoxious w/its sense of humor to the point where its running jokes are driven into the ground, & the main characters don't sell their internal struggles.

#ThorLoveAndThunder: Hoo boy. Credit to Taika for trying to make a comic book movie in the style of an early 80s rock opera, Christian Bale for turning in a solid performance as the villain, as well as an action sequence for its striking visuals & staging. The rest is a dud.
